erage. It seems like normal use would require the provider to be installed or specified, which makes sense. I think the generated test needs to call Conscrypt.newProvider() or include it somehow. But then, I wonder if that’s considered “beyond normal generated test scaffold.” Typically, the scaffold test probably starts off empty, and any usage code would come from the agent, right?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying provider setups**\\n\\nI'm looking at a concrete provider but wondering about the surrounding environment. Existing tests point to functionality, but does no_action imply no setup? It might still need agent guidance. JSON includes a relevant field, which is puzzling. The goal seems to be determining a deterministic setup without generic usage guidance. It’s interesting that the existing agent can research but is asking about typical library usage to finalize the setup. Plus, there could be an external dependency for generating certs.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting JVM tests**\\n\\nI’m considering that if we run tests on the JVM without using add-opens, there’s a chance they could fail. However, it looks like `javaTest` might actually use add-opens. I think it would be a good idea to look at the open-source Conscrypt README to check its setup for Java 9 modules. Let’s see if I can search for that and gather more information!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_pqkBfrgwnyCtFH85JnF0abqL|fc_028604bc4e8ea44f016a42de10cb20819493218cd95903e5fe", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request\nfor name in ['README.md','BUILDING.md','CAPABILITIES.md']:\n data=urllib.request.urlopen(f'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/google/conscrypt/master/{name}', timeout=20).read().decode('utf-8','replace')\n print('\\n---',name,'---')\n for term in ['add-opens','native.workdir','provider','Security.insertProviderAt','enable-native-access']:\n  i=data.lower().find(term.lower())\n  if i!=-1: print(term, data[max(0,i-300):i+500])\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1996, "output": 1711, "cacheRead": 47616, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 51323, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782767089871, "responseId": "resp_028604bc4e8ea44f016a42ddf3047c8194ad92f36a94ca2b8a"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_pqkBfrgwnyCtFH85JnF0abqL|fc_028604bc4e8ea44f016a42de10cb20819493218cd95903e5fe", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "\n--- README.md ---\nprovider # What’s changing\n\nAs part of this shift, we will no longer be able to accept external pull requests on GitHub.\n\n### What do you need to do\n\n*   Immediately, nothing.\n*   For Android developers, we recommend leveraging the Conscrypt version built into the Android platform, which is also the default provider.\n\nWe appreciate the Conscrypt community and look forward to continuing to offer a secure and efficient security provider.\n\n## Guidance for Android App Developers:\n\nMost Android devices include Conscrypt as a core part of the platform's security providers. The Java Cryptography Architecture (JCA) framework allows for multiple security providers, and the system selects one when you request a cryptographic algorithm implementation (like Cipher, SSLContext, MessageDigest, etc.).\n\n### Using \n\n--- BUILDING.md ---\n\n--- CAPABILITIES.md ---\nprovider dding`\n* `RSA/ECB/OAEPWithSHA-384AndMGF1Padding`\n* `RSA/ECB/OAEPWithSHA-512AndMGF1Padding`\n* `RSA/ECB/PKCS1Padding`\n\nConscrypt's OAEP ciphers (eg, `RSA/ECB/OAEPWithSHA-256AndMGF1Padding`) use the\nnamed digest for both the main digest and the MGF1 digest. This differs from\nthe behavior of some other providers, including the ones bundled with OpenJDK,\nwhich always use SHA-1 for the MGF1 digest. For maximum compatibility, you\nshould use `RSA/ECB/OAEPPadding` and initialize it with an\n[`OAEPParameterSpec`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/javax/crypto/spec/OAEPParameterSpec.html).\n\n### AlgorithmParameters\n\n* `AES`\n* `ChaCha20`\n* `DESEDE`\n* `EC`\n* `GCM`\n* `OAEP`\n* `PSS`\n\nConscrypt's EC AlgorithmParameters implementation only supports named curves.\n\n### CertificateFactory\n\n* `X509`\n\n###\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782767122019}]}
